  The physical significance of this latter approximation is that the disturbances near the
  time when the instability is zero are the only ones which have any appreciable ultimate
  effect. Those which occur earlier are damped out by the subsequent period of stability.
  Those which occur later have a shorter period of instability within which to develop to
  greater amplitude. This principle is familiar in radio, and is fundamental to the theory of
  the superregenerative receiver.
