  (4)
  Very little has yet been said about the effect of considering non-linear reaction rate
  functions when far from homogeneity. Any treatm ent so systematic as that given for the
  linear case seems to be out of the question. It is possible, however, to reach some qualitative
  conclusions about the effects of non-linear terms. Suppose that z x is the amplitude of the
  Fourier component which is most unstable (on a basis of the linear terms), and which may
  be supposed to have wave-length A. The non-linear terms will cause components with wave­
  lengths f A, JA, JA,... to appear as well as a space-independent component. If only quadratic
  terms are taken into account and if these are somewhat small, then the component of wave­
  length }A and the space-independent component will be the strongest. Suppose these have
  amplitudes z2and z v The state of the system is thus being described by the numbers z0,
